Passage:
In the case of Williams v. Florida, 399 U.S. 78 (1970), the Supreme Court held that a six-person jury in a criminal trial does not violate the Sixth Amendment right to a trial by an impartial jury. The Court reasoned that the number of jurors does not affect the fairness of the trial and that a smaller jury can still represent a fair cross-section of the community.

However, in Duncan v. Louisiana, <targetCase>391 U.S. 145</targetCase> (1968), the Supreme Court had previously held that the Fourteenth Amendment guarantees a right to trial by jury in all criminal cases that would come within the Sixth Amendment's guarantee if they were to be tried in a federal court. The question then is whether the constitutional guarantee of a trial by "jury" necessarily requires trial by exactly 12 persons, rather than some lesser number.

In Duncan v. Louisiana, the Court had reviewed the history of the development of trial by jury in criminal cases and found that it revealed a long tradition attaching great importance to the concept of relying on a body of one's peers to determine guilt or innocence as a safeguard against arbitrary law enforcement. However, the Court also found that the history afforded little insight into the considerations that gradually led to the size of the jury being generally fixed at 12.

In Williams v. Florida, the Court concluded that the 12-man requirement is not an indispensable component of the Sixth Amendment and that the essential feature of a jury lies in the interposition between the accused and his accuser of the commonsense judgment of a group of laymen, and in the community participation and shared responsibility that results from that group's determination of guilt or innocence. The Court found that the performance of this role is not a function of the particular number of the body that makes up the jury.

Therefore, based on the passage provided, the Target Case of Duncan v. Louisiana has not been overruled, as the Court in Williams v. Florida still recognizes the importance of the concept of relying on a body of one's peers to determine guilt or innocence as a safeguard against arbitrary law enforcement. However, the Court in Williams v. Florida has clarified that the number of jurors does not affect the fairness of the trial and that a smaller jury can still represent a fair cross-section of the community.
